04220nam a22005895i 9780822393184DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223931847 a10.1515/97808223931842doi  a(DE-B1597)553843  a(OCoLC)1170343628  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM656b.F74 2010eb 7aLIT0041602bisacsh04a306.76/6012221 aFreeman, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTime Binds :bQueer Temporalities, Queer Histories /cElizabeth Freeman; Lisa Lowe, Judith Halberstam. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b21 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerverse Modernities: A Series Edited by Jack Halberstam and Lisa Lowe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Queer and Not Now -- tOne. Junk Inheritances, Bad Timing -- tTwo. Deep Lez -- tThree. Time Binds, or, Erotohistoriography -- tFour. Turn the Beat Around -- tCoda -- tAppendix. Distributors for Films and Videos -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTime Binds is a powerful argument that temporal and sexual dissonance are intertwined, and that the writing of history can be both embodied and erotic. Challenging queer theory's recent emphasis on loss and trauma, Elizabeth Freeman foregrounds bodily pleasure in the experience and representation of time as she interprets an eclectic archive of queer literature, film, video, and art. She examines work by visual artists who emerged in a commodified, "postfeminist," and "postgay" world. Yet they do not fully accept the dissipation of political and critical power implied by the idea that various political and social battles have been won and are now consigned to the past. By privileging temporal gaps and narrative detours in their work, these artists suggest ways of putting the past into meaningful, transformative relation with the present. Such "queer asynchronies" provide opportunities for rethinking historical consciousness in erotic terms, thereby countering the methods of traditional and Marxist historiography. Central to Freeman's argument are the concepts of chrononormativity, the use of time to organize individual human bodies toward maximum productivity; temporal drag, the visceral pull of the past on the supposedly revolutionary present; and erotohistoriography, the conscious use of the body as a channel for and means of understanding the past. Time Binds emphasizes the critique of temporality and history as crucial to queer politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHomosexualityxSocial aspects. 0aQueer theory. 0aTimexSocial aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh1 aHalberstam, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLowe, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393184zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393184.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles